{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"62c9da0c-3bfe-4c9d-8f5f-ebc1bd272c9d","content":"There's no repo-specific guidance here, so here's the general approach:\n\n**Replace `VSTest@3` with `DotNetCoreCLI@2` (or a plain `dotnet test` script step):**\n\n```yaml\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run tests (Microsoft.Testing.Platform)'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*.Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >\n      --configuration Release\n      --logger \"trx;LogFileName=results.trx\"\n      --collect \"Code Coverage\"\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n\n1. **Enable the new platform** – in each test `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n   <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n   ```\n\n2. **TRX reports** – the `--logger trx` argument still works; publish with:\n   ```yaml\n   - task: PublishTestResults@2\n     inputs:\n       testResultsFormat: VSTest\n       testResultsFiles: '**/*.trx'\n   ```\n\n3. **Code coverage** – use `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` (or add `coverlet` with `--collect:\"XPlat Code Coverage\"`) and publish:\n   ```yaml\n   - task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n     inputs:\n       codeCoverageTool: Cobertura\n       summaryFileLocation: '**/coverage.cobertura.xml'\n   ```\n\n4. **Remove** the `VSTest@3` task entirely — `dotnet test` now invokes the test platform directly since your projects are self-contained executables.\n\nThe main conceptual shift: tests are standalone executables; the runner is embedded, so you no longer need the VSTest task adapter.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"39b5c9af-57a5-4772-b4c4-6068f262a786","outputTokens":431,"requestId":"E3D6:14EAB3:16716FA:1910279:6A052041"},"id":"abb23d72-26eb-41e5-84da-04e37322610f","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:07:23.852Z","parentId":"86156691-1b44-47cc-bd30-901be3fa8e6e"}
